{{Infobox SCOTUS case |Litigants=United Automobile Workers v. Johnson Controls, Inc. |ArgueDate=October 10 |ArgueYear=1990 |DecideDate=March 21 |DecideYear=1991 |FullName= International Union, United Automobile, Aerospace & Agricultural Implement Workers Of America, UAW, et al. vs. Johnson Controls, Inc. |USVol= 499 |USPage=187 |ParallelCitations=111 S. Ct. 1196; 113 [[L. Ed. 2d]] 158 |Docket=89-1215 |OralArgument=https://www.oyez.org/cases/1990-1999/1990/1990_89_1215 |OpinionAnnouncement=https://www.oyez.org/cases/1990-1999/1990/1990_89_1215 |Prior=680 [[F. Supp.]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/district-courts/FSupp/680/309/1526531/ 309] ([[E.D. Wis.]] 1988); affirmed, 886 [[F.2d]] [https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/F2/886/871/18935/ 871] ([[7th Cir.]] 1989); [[Certiorari|cert]]. granted, {{ussc|494|1055|1990|el=no}}. |Subsequent= |Holding=Title VII, as amended by the Pregnancy Discrimination Act of 1978, forbids sex-specific fetal-protection policies, as incapability of becoming pregnant is not a "bona fide occupational qualification." |SCOTUS=1990-1991 |Majority=Blackmun |JoinMajority=Marshall, Stevens, O'Connor, Souter |Concurrence=White |JoinConcurrence=Rehnquist, Kennedy |Concurrence2=Scalia |Dissent= |JoinDissent= |LawsApplied=[[Pregnancy Discrimination Act of 1978]] }} '''''United Automobile Workers v. Johnson Controls, Inc.''''' 499 U.S. 187 (1991), was a decision by the [[Supreme Court of the United States]] establishing that [[private sector]] policies prohibiting women from knowingly working in potentially hazardous occupations are [[gender discrimination|discriminatory]] and in violation of [[Title VII]] and the [[Pregnancy Discrimination Act]] of 1978.<ref>{{ussc|name=United Automobile Workers v. Johnson Controls, Inc.|volume=499|page=187|pin=|year=1991}}.</ref> At the time the case was heard, it was considered one of the most important sex-discrimination cases since the passage of Title VII.<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Presser|first1=Arlynn Leiber|last2=Bertin|first2=Joan|title=Women at Work: Should 'Fetal Protection' Policies Be Upheld|journal=ABA Journal|date=June 1990|volume=76|issue=6|pages=38–39|publisher=American Bar Association}}</ref>
==Opinion of the Court== The [[majority opinion]] by [[Harry Blackmun|Justice Blackmun]] held that that Title VII prohibits gender–specific [[fetal protection policies]]. Hence based on that statute, the Court decided against [[Johnson Controls]] by concluding that the company’s fetal protection policy contravened Title VII of the Civil Rights Act of 1964, as amended by the [[Pregnancy Discrimination Act|PDA]]; and the company's gender-specific rule was biased and inequitable because it permitted fertile men, but not fertile women, to decide whether to work in jobs subjected to lead exposure while manufacturing batteries.<ref name=Meze> {{cite encyclopedia | last =Mezey | first = Susan Gluck | title =UAW v. Johnson Controls, 499 U.S. 187 (1991) | volume = Volume 5 | publisher =Macmillan Reference USA | encyclopedia =Encyclopedia of the Supreme Court of the United States | date =2008 | url =http://ic.galegroup.com/ic/uhic/CaseOverviewDetailsPage/CaseOverviewDetailsWindow?failOverType=&query=&prodId=UHIC&windowstate=normal&contentModules=&display-query=&mode=view&displayGroupName=Case-Overview&limiter=&currPage=&disableHighlighting=false&displayGroups=&sortBy=&search_within_results=&p=UHIC%3AWHIC&action=e&catId=&activityType=&scanId=&documentId=GALE%7CCX3241201020&source=Bookmark&u=mlin_c_marlpl&jsid=69e82d6fcffe30da41b72d1516972515 | format =Gale: U.S. History in Context}}</ref><ref name=Shapiro> {{cite web | last =Shapiro | first =Robert A. (Associate Solicitor for Legislation and Legal Counsel) | authorlink = | title = Policy guidance on the Supreme Court Decision | work = | website = | publisher =Occupational Safety & Health Administration | date = July 11, 1991 | url =https://www.osha.gov/pls/oshaweb/owadisp.show_document?p_table=INTERPRETATIONS&p_id=20332}}</ref><ref> Bernstein, Andrew Evan (1992). "[http://scholarlycommons.law.hofstra.edu/hlelj/vol9/iss2/5/ UAW v. Johnson Controls: A Final Word on Fetal Protection Policies and Their Effect on Women's Rights in Today's Economy]." Hofstra Labor and Employment Law Journal '''9.2''': 5.</ref><ref name=Jennings> {{cite book | last = Jennings | first = Marianne | authorlink = | title =Business: Its Legal, Ethical, and Global Environment | publisher =[[Cengage]] Learning | series = | volume = | edition = | date =2015 | location =Canada | pages =715–722 | language = | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=JebKAgAAQBAJ&pg=PA721&dq=By+excluding+women+with+childbearing+capacity+from+lead-exposed+jobs,+respondent%27s+policy+creates+a+facial+classification+based+on+gender+and+explicit&hl=en&sa=X&ei=-s-QVc23Esj1-QHqwrzICA&ved=0CCAQ6AEwAA#v=onepage&q=By%20excluding%20women%20with%20childbearing%20capacity%20from%20lead-exposed%20jobs%2C%20respondent%27s%20policy%20creates%20a%20facial%20classification%20based%20on%20gender%20and%20explicit&f=false | isbn =}}</ref><ref name=schnied> {{cite book | last = Schneid | first = Thomas D. | authorlink = | title =Discrimination Law Issues for the Safety Professional | publisher = CRC Press; Google Books | date =2012 | location =Boca Raton, Florida | pages =168–171 | language = | url =https://books.google.com/books?id=GEmD8k35swsC&pg=PA169&lpg=PA169&dq=By+excluding+women+with+childbearing+capacity+from+lead-exposed+jobs,+respondent%27s+policy+creates+a+facial+classification+based+on+gender+and+explicit&source=bl&ots=-1ob1ekijk&sig=VlU3v9H5roKuMtUyfqY08hIMF1k&hl=en&sa=X&ei=GsOQVcfvK4Sv-AHW3J9Y&ved=0CCwQ6AEwAw#v=onepage&q=By%20excluding%20women%20with%20childbearing%20capacity%20from%20lead-exposed%20jobs%2C%20respondent%27s%20policy%20creates%20a%20facial%20classification%20based%20on%20gender%20and%20explicit&f=false | isbn = }}</ref><ref name=Oyez> {{cite web | last = | first = | authorlink = | title =United Automobile Workers v. Johnson Controls, Inc | work = | website =0YEZ Project | publisher =Chicago-Kent College of Law | date =2015 | url =https://www.oyez.org/cases/1990-1999/1990/1990_89_1215 | format =Web page with Audio Files }} Audio fil